Version Backup 2014-08-19¶{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Garamond;}{\f1\fnil\fcharset0 Arial;}}{&1310}{\colortbl ;\red128\green128\blue128;\red255\green255\blue255;}{&1310}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\fi720\sl480\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\f0\fs22 {&1310}\par {&1310}\par \cf2\f1 {&1310}\par \cf1\f0 "Oh my god don't look behind you."{&1310}\par "What-?" I'd already twisted around before Tess could even finish.{&1310}\par We were sitting at Bertram's bar out front. After a lot of long-overdue snipes, jokes, and chiding remarks -- mostly Tess and Bertram going at it -- the old man finally calmed down enough to practically strangle me to death in a bearhug while saying how pale and half-starved I looked. Once the excitement started to wear down, it was hard to get him to let me go until Tess interjected something about me being the favorite even though he hadn't adopted \i me\i0 .{&1310}\par "To hell with ya I would have if I'd know how much damned troubled you'd be, girl!" he'd snapped at her and she laughed before getting chased out of the kitchen. "Bless her heart for putting up with a fat, old man a little longer," he'd also added once she was out of earshot like always, "I'd probably have died if I'd seen the both of you go off all at once."{&1310}\par I followed Tess out front while Bertram promised to have something for us to eat as quick as he could. I found the other woman lounging at the bar, still smoking, and we hadn't been there three minutes when she finally said \i that\i0 .{&1310}\par At first I couldn't even tell what she was talking about. There were plenty of people scattered around the room for the afternoon crowd, coming and going, eating and drinking in the sometimes-bright-sometimes-dark, off-color mood lighting. Tess muttered something under her breath I couldn't make out, but it sounded frustrated. Then I figured it out. Some guy in a ruffled jacket over a tech coat was standing just inside the front doors, looking around. He found me and Tess at the bar and started forward in a rush.{&1310}\par "He's coming over here, isn't he?" Tess hissed across the not-so-clean counter at me, head hunched low.{&1310}\par "Yeah ..." I told her, coming back around.{&1310}\par "Fuck!"{&1310}\par "Who the hell is he?"{&1310}\par "Ughhhh ..." she just growled disgust in her throat. And before she could think to actually answer me, that guy was suddenly looming over her other shoulder.{&1310}\par "You haven't called me," he blurted out almost immediately, before she even got the chance to acknowledge him. Like they knew each other pretty well. Which was funny because I was pretty damn sure Tess would have said something if she'd met anyone like that. It should have been the \i first\i0  thing out of her mouth after I got off the transport.{&1310}\par Tess tilted her head back, puffing out exaggeratedly as she looked up at the ceiling and sighed.{&1310}\par "I've been busy."{&1310}\par "For three weeks," was the flat, rhetorical question out of his mouth. But she answered it anyways.{&1310}\par "Uh -- \i yeah\i0 ."{&1310}\par "Doing what?"{&1310}\par "None of your fucking business, that's what."{&1310}\par There was a pause as he seemed to gauge her and I got a better look at him without being too obvious. Tall, thin, dark-trimmed hair and sallow cheeks, that jacket he was hiding -- definitely a lab rat on the station. His collar beneath the civvie coat said naval lieutenant commander in rank, and he looked in his thirties -- maybe a ten years older than Tess. He had a practiced sort of calm on the surface but there was ... \i something\i0  ... I don't know -- \i off\i0 .{&1310}\par "I left you plenty of messages," he continued, and Tess waved a hand.{&1310}\par "Yeah, well, I must've missed 'em."{&1310}\par He snatched her arm in midair and twisted it over, exposing her comm unit beneath the sleeve. "No, you didn't. You've been deliberately ignoring me."{&1310}\par "Hey, what the fuck!" she yanked her hand back.{&1310}\par "Theresa-" he started.{&1310}\par "Don't freaking call me that!"{&1310}\par "I don't think you understand how important this is -- I," he glanced around quickly -- still not noticing me there at all, I guess -- and then ducked in closer like he had some big secret, "... I told you all about the implications. It ... I mean, it'll be revolutionary! You understand that right?" He was pushing in close to whisper excitedly at her, and didn't seem to notice her pulling herself even further back away from him. "Please, you \i have\i0  to come see my latest work in the lab. I need someone to--," he caught himself, and then continued, "I need \i you\i0  to be there this time."{&1310}\par He was excited, bristling all over with that energized, all-consuming look that his type sometimes got whenever they'd do something new and were so full of themselves and what they did that they simply \i had\i0  to tell everyone. Or at least someone. In this case, I guess -- Tess.{&1310}\par She just gave him a shifty look.{&1310}\par "Uh, well -- I mean, I would, but ..." And she abruptly snatched me up by the arm, pulling me halfway right out of my seat.{&1310}\par "\i Hey\i0 -"{&1310}\par "But my best friend just got back from basic training and I, um ... promised to hang out with her for the next two weeks. So I'll be \i way\i0  too busy for a while.{&1310}\par "Uh, hi," I managed, but Tess still wouldn't let me go. {&1310}\par I cleared my throat and still, she hung on.{&1310}\par "Two weeks," the guy started to say, not even really caring that I was there. Not that that bothered me at all since I was pretty sure I didn't want to meet him anyways. But then he did look at me, while I was trying to pull myself free of Tess weirdly vicious deathgrip. He saw the motion and followed her hand to my arm up to my face and stopped in midsentence, and stared. All that nervous energy went right out of him and he was suddenly still.{&1310}\par Tess had her mouth open like she was already getting ready to say something back, but didn't. She noticed him and then slowly looked from that guy to me with a slow turn of her pink head. Her eyes bounced back and forth in a "what the fuck?" sort of way a few times before she finally did something, the whole while with me sitting there suddenly being eyeballed by her creepy-as-fuck wannabe boyfriend.{&1310}\par "Brant-?"{&1310}\par "Excuse me." His words practically jumped on top of hers in a rush to get out of his mouth. Then he was gone. Just ... gone. Just - a hasty, awkward scramble to climb over himself back toward the exit. We both watched him go.{&1310}\par "Woah," was all Tess could say about that for a few seconds. I glanced around the bar once he was gone to see if anyone else had noticed how fucking weird that way. I guess I was the only one, though. And Tess too.{&1310}\par "I can't figure out if he likes you," Tess finally continued, still staring, "or hates you."{&1310}\par "What is \i that\i0  supposed to mean?"{&1310}\par She ignored me, just shaking her head. Eventually she shrugged. "Either way, I guess he won't be bugging me as much if I keep you around. Oh \i god\i0 ," she abruptly slumped on her stool, "you'll be gone again \i way\i0  too soon."{&1310}\par  Before I could even get irritated at the fact that she was more worried about that guy harassing her than me \i leaving\i0  again, she had already pulled another cigarette and started to light up.{&1310}\par "Who the hell even \i was\i0  that guy?" I asked instead.{&1310}\par "I don't know," she shook her head, "or care." She breathed out smoke. "Not seeing me or anything, if that's what you think."{&1310}\par "I hope not."{&1310}\par "No fucking way. He just came in here some night a while ago and started hitting on me. I think I told you about him in one of those messages I sent you."{&1310}\par I remembered now. {&1310}\par "Yeah, I think so."{&1310}\par "He, uh, well I found out he was working in one of the more 'restricted' areas," she crooked her fingers in the air as she said it, "and I, well, I thought I'd get a closer look since he offered ..."{&1310}\par I almost burst out laughing, but I caught myself before the whole room heard it. Tess had a way too innocent look on her face as she said it not to laugh. "Anything interesting?" I managed to ask.{&1310}\par "Not really," she sighed, and deflated. Then she turned and tapped out ash from her cigarette on Bertram's side of the bar while he wasn't there and looking. "Not enough to put up with him creepin' on me all the time now. Fucking weirdo."{&1310}\par The kitchen doors flashed open and Tess' hand instantly withdrew from across the bar like it'd never been there. Too bad the first thing Bertram noticed as he came out with two steaming plates of what was supposed to look like beef, potatoes, and corn -- but was really just gussied up nutrient rations -- was that ash on the deck as he stepped in it.{&1310}\par "What the-"{&1310}\par He jumped back, looking sharply at his shoes. Then he stuck a fat finger in Tess' face. His own scrunched up into a craggy, pudgy mass. "I'm gonna leave that for your shift tonight!"{&1310}\par "Whaaat."{&1310}\par "Yeah, that's right, girl. Done more than my fair share of cleaning up after you. This one can wait. Just for \i you\i0 ."{&1310}\par "You mean I have to come in to\i night\i0 ? It's Ev's first day back!"{&1310}\par "I don't care if it's her fucking \i birthday\i0  you ..."{&1310}\par {&1310}\par \pard\sl480\slmult1\qc *\tab *\tab *{&1310}\par \pard\fi720\sl480\slmult1 "Tess ..." I mumbled to myself in the dark. "Dad? Bertram ... where are you?"{&1310}\par I was moving down the hallway toward where that scream had come from and I stumbled, pitching forward. A sharp pain lanced through my head like someone had just burned a hole between the backs of my eyes and-{&1310}\par "GET OUT!"{&1310}\par My face was squished up against the floor, some voice ringing in my ears. There was anger, flaring up and burning all the fear to ash. It drowned me inside it.{&1310}\par I worked to curl up into a little ball there against the deck -- to disappear intot he metal and vanish forever. I tried to cry out but nothing would come from my mouth. My eyes watered until I couldn't see and then I squeezed them shut.{&1310}\par Then, just as quickly as that pain had started -- it stopped.{&1310}\par I was lying on the floor, tears in my eyes, and struggling tob reathe.{&1310}\par What ...{&1310}\par ... the ...{&1310}\par I couldn't even finish the thought. It felt like someone had punched me right in the stomach and knocked the wind out of me except replace stomach with brain and wind with ... I didn't even know. Sanity? Consciousness? Probably that, since I lost time there, curled up int he dark. It was dizzying and enervating and for too long I couldn't even move -- didn't \i want\i0  to move.{&1310}\par If some pirate had come up and shot me right then and there I probably wouldn't have cared. I felt sick to my ... \i everything\i0 .{&1310}\par It passed, though. Eventually, it passed.{&1310}\par I half threw up as I tried to pick myself back up from the deck. Drool was leaking out of the side of my mouth back down to the floor. I had to blink exasperatedly to clear my eyes and even that didn't do it so I tried scrubbign at them with an unresponsive hand. I ended up toppling over to one side.{&1310}\par \i You're going to die. The station is under attack and you're going to die. Get up or you're going to die here\i0 -{&1310}\par It must have taken me five whole minutes to slowly pick myself back up again. All the while I started to remember that scream and how close it had probably been. And how it had cut off.{&1310}\par I hobbled along a few steps forward. I had to catch my balance against the bulkhead. There were more labs here, branching off to either side and swimming in view as my brain felt like it was still trying to flop around inside my head. It took me a little while and another  meter or so of stumbling over myself to realize how much more wrecked these labs were than the ones in the next deck. Equipment was scattered all over the place like someone had raged out in one. I staggered to the other side of the corridor and noticed the shattered glass and blood in another. No body, though. I didn't find the first body until after I'd felt my hand scrape against the plasma scoring on the wall.\cf2\f1 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
